<Base title="About" description="Scientist, immigrant, builder. The improbable arc from Sverdlovsk to Oakland.">
  <h1>About</h1>

  <p>I was born in Yekaterinburg — then Sverdlovsk — in 1981, capital of the Urals and site of the 1979 Soviet anthrax leak. My family left the Soviet Union in the late 1980s, passing through Austria and Italy as stateless refugees before reaching the United States.</p>

  <p>I never graduated high school. I dropped out of Newton North in 1998. But while still a teenager, I was doing IT consulting at the Harvard Club, taking evening classes at Harvard Extension, winning Massachusetts chess championships, and managing a remote programming team in Russia for LinuxFund.org.</p>

  <h2>Education</h2>
  <p>Brandeis (B.A. Physics, Math, English, High Honors) → Cambridge (M.Phil. European Literature, on a Cambridge Trust Bursary) → Woods Hole MBL (Physiology Course, Hearst Scholar) → UCSF (Ph.D. Biophysics, NSF Fellow, published in <em>Nature</em>).</p>

  <p>My PhD was on how molecular machines position information along DNA — chromatin remodelers that act as dimeric motors to space nucleosomes. I studied under Geeta Narlikar. Before that, I did computational neuroscience with Larry Abbott at Brandeis and mapped galaxy clusters at Fermilab on the Sloan Digital Sky Survey.</p>

  <h2>Companies</h2>
  <p><strong>Sourcery</strong> (YC W13, 2011-2017) — B2B food commerce platform. Clients included Palantir, Dropbox, Airbnb, Stripe. Raised $7.5M+. Acquired by Lavu.</p>
  <p><strong>Cheetah Technologies</strong> (2015-2018) — Restaurant supply chain. Co-founder, Chief Data Scientist. $66M+ raised.</p>
  <p><strong>ImmuneBridge</strong> (2020-2024) — Allogeneic NK cell immunotherapies from cord blood. Co-founder & CEO. $17.6M raised from Insight Partners and M Ventures.</p>
  <p><strong>Pioneer Fund</strong> (2017-present) — Venture Partner. YC alumni fund, healthcare and AI.</p>

  <h2>Adventures</h2>
  <p><strong>Afghanistan</strong> (2010-2011) — Field coordinator with Synergy Strike Force in Jalalabad. Coached the Nangarhar Province basketball team in the national tournament. Set up telemedicine sessions linking Afghan female doctors with Pakistani specialists. <a href="/archive">Wrote about it</a>.</p>
  <p><strong>Central Asia</strong> — Drove 10,000 miles across the continent, from Europe through Uzbekistan and Kyrgyzstan. Got arrested in Kazakhstan and represented myself in court.</p>
  <p><strong>Sailing</strong> — 1,000 miles down the US East Coast on a boat called Borka.</p>
  <p><strong>Beijing</strong> — NSF fellow at Peking University during the 2008 Olympics. Documented informal recycling economies for <a href="/archive">Trash City</a>.</p>

  <h2>Writing</h2>
  <p>Published in <em>Wired</em>, <em>n+1</em>, <em>HuffPost</em>, <em>Medium</em>, <em>Food+Tech Connect</em>, <em>NPR</em>, and <em>Nature</em>. My Medium piece about getting arrested as a Good Samaritan in San Francisco went viral across seven outlets including Boing Boing and Reason.</p>

  <h2>Photography</h2>
  <p>1,638 files on Wikimedia Commons, 245 used across 106 Wikipedia language editions. 5,330 photos on Flickr. My fight-or-flight response illustration appears on 30+ language Wikipedias.</p>

  <h2>Other</h2>
  <p>Co-founded <strong>Langton Labs</strong> (2007-2016), a science/art collective in San Francisco featured in the NYT and WSJ. Co-founded <strong>Phage Camp</strong> at Burning Man — 200 scientists, a 3-million-volt Tesla coil, Caltech IQIM collaborations.</p>
  <p>Languages: English (native), Russian (native), Italian (fluent), Hebrew (proficient).</p>
  <p>Massachusetts State Chess Champion, age group (1992, 1993, 1994). 4th place at the US National Championship (1994).</p>

  <h2>Now</h2>
  <p>I live in Oakland with my children. I'm building personal AI infrastructure — multi-agent systems, voice memo indexing, knowledge graphs — and writing about what it means to point artificial intelligence at your own life. I have 1,238 voice memos spanning 17 years and 921 hours. I'm indexing them all.</p>

